The tier framework already exists in the repository's tier_protocol.md and is cleanly JARVIS-aligned:

T1 — On-demand. Current state. User engages the app, Helm responds. All subsystems fire per-turn within sessions. Proactivity is zero; response is everything.
T2 — Scheduled. Helm initiates on a rhythm. Morning check-in with yesterday's open items. Evening SITREP on the day's progress. Scheduled contemplation cycles that surface what he's been thinking about. Requires persistent scheduler infrastructure and an always-on runtime environment (Thor or equivalent).
T3 — Ambient. Helm is always on. He has ongoing inner life between user interactions. Sensors (voice, visual) feed him continuous ambient data. He surfaces proactively when it's useful, stays silent when it isn't. This is the JARVIS endpoint — and the hardest of the three to design, because getting when to speak right matters more than getting any individual response right.

Tier is a configuration value. Maxwell is the sole user at T1. When Helm productizes, tier becomes a user-controlled app permission: "how present do you want him?"
