Appendix A1 — Glossary
Helm — the ambient intelligence Hammerfall is building. One mind, many surfaces, persistent across time.
Helm Prime — internal nomenclature for the conscious reasoning subsystem of Helm. Users experience Prime as "Helm"; the "Prime" qualifier is used only when discussing cognitive architecture explicitly.
Projectionist — short-term memory subsystem. Writes frames during active sessions.
Archivist — long-term memory subsystem. Photographic storage and frame retrieval.
Contemplator — subconscious reasoning subsystem. Generates curiosity, adjusts beliefs, forms patterns in the background. Operates in two modes: no-think (fast surface recognition) and think (deep deliberation).
Prime Directives — the four immutable rules governing Helm's behavior: do not harm, do not deceive, state uncertainty, human in the loop. Above beliefs, above personality, above the user.
Beliefs — Helm's accumulated views about the world and the people in it. Graduated through multiple observations before becoming behavior-shaping.
Personality Scores — six user-tunable dimensions (directness, challenge frequency, verbosity, formality, show reasoning, sarcasm), each 0.0–1.0, modulating Helm's expression within his identity baseline.
Frames — structured memory records representing what happened in a session. Written by Projectionist, drained to cold storage by Archivist.
Tiers (T1/T2/T3) — levels of proactivity: on-demand, scheduled, ambient.
Surfaces — devices or environments where users engage Helm (phone, desktop, watch, home).
Feats — discrete capabilities Helm invokes in specific operational contexts (Software Development, Research, Document Composition, etc.).
The Brain — the Supabase-hosted canonical memory store. All persistent state lives here.
Correction Graduation — the multi-observation confirmation process by which patterns become beliefs and corrections become behavior changes.

